Amy Bauman,aabhas@myasiavc.com,"The Angel Investor Forum (AIF), founded in 2004, is an organization located in Connecticut comprised of accredited investors, who are former CEOs, VCs, serial entrepreneurs, and active private equity investors. Due to the widening gap in the capital markets, there is a shortage of funding available at the seed stage ($250K-$5M). This funding gap represents a great opportunity for investment in companies and the group provides $100K to $2M for companies with substantial growth potential. AIF is not a fund; Investment members collaborate on due diligence, but make individual investment decisions (under common valuation and terms). The typical company the group looks at is raising between $750K and $1.5 Million. Members typically put in between $150K and $350K as a group. The individual investment is typically $25,000 but ranges from $10,000 (if the deal permits) to $100,000. The group's investment criteria includes: a clearly articulated market position, management team with a demonstrated track record, clear intellectual property strategy, defensible competitive position in an emerging or growth market, and an exit strategy for investors within 3-5 years.","United States, Connecticut United States, Hartford Connecticut United States, Americas, North America",Research,[],,Angel Investors / HNW,[],0,,,,"[""Seed Round""]","Health & Wellness (LOHAS), Deep Tech",,,,http://facebook.com/people/_/1138082762,http://www.linkedin.com/pub/amy-cohen-bauman/7/982/787,https://www.angelinvestorforum.com/,,,Amy Bauman,amycbauman@gmail.com,9148066251,"",http://www.linkedin.com/pub/amy-cohen-bauman/7/982/787,,http://facebook.com/people/_/1138082762,,,,,,,,,,,,,,
Steve Mixtacki,aabhas@myasiavc.com,"WARF is the Wisconsin Alumni Research Foundation, an independent, nonprofit foundation chartered to support research at the UW-Madison and the designated technology transfer organization for the university. WARF is a separate entity from the university but partners closely with it. WARF distributes the income from commercial licenses to the UW-Madison, the inventors and their departments. Each year, WARF contributes over $45 million to fund additional UW-Madison research. WARF maintains an investment fund it may use to invest in its start-up companies that meet certain criteria, including the requirement of a suitable co-investor. WARF currently is working with more than 50 active start-ups whose business markets include therapeutics, research tools, biotechnology, medical devices, food and agriculture, engineering, computer, stem cell and clean technologies. WARF currently holds equity in more than 35 of these companies.","United States, Wisconsin United States, Madison Wisconsin United States, Americas, North America, Great Lakes",Research,[],,Angel Investors / HNW,[],0,,,,"[""Seed Round""]","Medical Devices, Health & Wellness (LOHAS), Agriculture, Deep Tech, CleanTech",,,,https://www.warf.org/,,,,,Steve Mixtacki,"",+1 (608) 261-1954,"",,,https://www.warf.org/,,,,,,,,,,,,,,
Joseph Sparacio,aabhas@myasiavc.com," David Kirkpatrick is a Co-Founder and serves as a Managing Director at SJF Ventures. He focuses on high growth, positive impact ventures. The fund has offices in Durham, NC, New York and San Francisco, and was founded in 1999. Dave helped lead SJF's capitalization of three funds totaling $135 million. The most recent fund, SJF Ventures III, was closed at $90 million in the spring of 2013 and was oversubscribed. SJF Ventures has invested in 47 portfolio companies and David currently serves on the boards of NEXTracker, Entouch Controls, Community Energy, groSolar, and ED MAP. Dave's particular industry focus areas include energy efficiency, recycling & reuse, solar, and M2M enabled resource efficiency companies. Previous to SJF, Dave founded and managed two other successful enterprises - KirkWorks, a cleantech investment consulting firm, and SunShares, a solar energy, and recycling company. Dave was named the national 2005 CDVC Practitioner of the Year by the Community Development Venture Capital Alliance and Recycler of the Year in 1996, the National Recycling Coalition's award for leadership in the recycling industry. Dave co-founded the SJF Institute in 2001 which merged with Investors' Circle, an impact investment angel network, in 2011. He is a frequent public speaker on venture capital, cleantech innovation and impacts investing. Dave earned a BA in Physics and History from Duke University in 1982 and an MBA from UNC Kenan-Flagler Business School (KFBS) in 1991. He was named KFBS Executive MBA Alumni of the Year in 2010. He also serves on Board of TransLoc.","United States, North Carolina United States, Americas, North America",Research,[],,Angel Investors / HNW,[],0,,,,"[""Seed Round""]","HR Tech, Logistics, Health & Wellness (LOHAS), Wellness, Education, Food and Beverage, HealthTech, Mobility, CleanTech",,,,https://twitter.com/dkirk855,http://www.linkedin.com/in/josephsparacio,https://angel.co/david-kirkpatrick-1,https://sjfventures.com/,,Joseph Sparacio,joseph@wacarefund.org,7162835270,"",http://www.linkedin.com/in/josephsparacio,https://twitter.com/dkirk855,https://angel.co/david-kirkpatrick-1,,,,,,,,,,,,,,
